# Rust design philosophy

Rust's type system is the design tool. Most of what other languages
solve with patterns or runtime checks, Rust solves with types. Use
that.

External companion reading: *Effective Rust* (David Drysdale),
*Rust for Rustaceans* (Jon Gjengset), the
[Rust API Guidelines](https://rust-lang.github.io/api-guidelines/).

## Make invalid states unrepresentable

The single most important Rust design principle.

- Use `enum` for sum types — anywhere you'd otherwise have "this string
  is either `'pending'`, `'paid'`, or `'refunded'`", an `enum` does it
  with compile-time exhaustiveness.
- Use the **newtype pattern** for primitives that mean something
  specific. `struct UserId(u64);` is one line and eliminates a whole
  class of "I passed an order id where a user id was expected" bugs.
- Use `Option<T>` for "may be absent" — never sentinel values, never
  `-1`-means-missing. `Option<T>` participates in exhaustive matching.
- Use `Result<T, E>` for "may fail" — never out-parameters, never
  global error state.
- Use the **type-state pattern** (different types for different states
  of an object) when the legal-operations-per-state set is non-trivial:
  `Builder<Unset>` → `Builder<Configured>` → `Built`.

If your function's contract reads "if X then Y must be set", that's a
type-state signal — encode it.

## Traits are interfaces; prefer composition

- Traits define behaviour, not identity. Don't reach for inheritance —
  Rust doesn't have it, and trying to fake it (deep trait hierarchies,
  `dyn` chains) defeats the borrow checker.
- For shared behaviour, compose: a struct *has-a* `Box<dyn Logger>`,
  or generic `L: Logger`.
- Static dispatch (`impl Trait`, `T: Trait`) is the default.
  Dynamic dispatch (`dyn Trait`) is for genuine heterogeneity (a
  `Vec<Box<dyn Renderer>>` of different renderer types).

## Ownership and borrowing — the layering rule

Think of ownership the way DDD thinks of aggregates: one owner per
piece of data, others borrow.

- Functions that **consume** the value: take `T` (by value).
- Functions that **read** the value: take `&T`.
- Functions that **mutate**: take `&mut T`.
- Don't take `&mut T` when `&T` would suffice — it forecloses
  parallelism for no gain.
- Lifetimes are not annotations to slap on until the compiler stops
  yelling — they document the relationship between borrows. When
  elision can't figure it out, name them in a way that makes the
  relationship readable (`<'src, 'dst>`, not `<'a, 'b>`).

## Builder pattern for non-trivial constructors

When a struct has 4+ configuration knobs or some are optional, use a
builder. The
[derive_builder](https://crates.io/crates/derive_builder) crate
handles the boilerplate, but a hand-written builder is fine too. Builders
combine cleanly with the type-state pattern (`Builder<Unset>` → `Built`).

## Errors as values

- Library code: define an error `enum` with `thiserror::Error`. One
  variant per failure mode. Implement `From` for any wrapped errors so
  `?` works.
- Application code: `anyhow::Result<T>`, with `.context("…")` at each
  layer of the call stack to leave a breadcrumb trail in the eventual
  error message.
- Cross the boundary once. The application's main use-case method
  returns `anyhow::Result`; the libraries it calls return their own
  typed errors which `?` lifts into `anyhow::Error`.

## Async is a colour — pick deliberately

- An entire crate is async or it isn't. Don't sprinkle `async fn` into
  a sync codebase; the await colour spreads.
- Pick **one** runtime per binary: tokio for most server work,
  embassy/async-std for embedded/special cases. Don't mix.
- Async traits are routine on stable now — write `trait Foo {
  async fn bar(&self); }` directly when targeting Rust 1.75+.
- Don't block in async code. `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` for the
  rare CPU-bound or sync-only operation.

## The Clean Architecture mapping

The DDD layering from `general/architecture.md` maps to Cargo crates
or modules:

| Layer | Rust expression |
| --- | --- |
| `domain` | Plain structs and enums with methods. No `tokio`, `sqlx`, `reqwest`. Trait definitions for what the domain *needs from the world* — `trait OrderRepository`. |
| `application` | Use-case functions / structs that take generic `R: OrderRepository`. |
| `infrastructure` | Concrete `impl OrderRepository for SqlxOrderRepo`. Imports the database driver. |
| `presentation` | `main.rs` + the HTTP framework. Wires concrete types into generics at startup. |

This is the same composition root idea: the place where `T = SqlxOrderRepo`
gets chosen exists once, at the program entry point.

## Don't fight the borrow checker — listen to it

When the compiler complains, it's usually pointing at a real design
problem, not a syntactic one. Common translations:

- "Cannot borrow `x` as mutable because it's already borrowed as
  immutable" → the function is doing two things; split it.
- "Cannot move out of borrowed content" → you're trying to consume
  something you only borrowed; either clone (knowing the cost) or
  rethink ownership.
- "Lifetime of `'a` does not outlive `'b`" → the data you're handing
  out doesn't live long enough; the caller needs to keep the owner
  alive longer, or you need to return owned data.

## Performance hygiene

Don't micro-optimise during design. Do default to:
- Avoid `Box<dyn ...>` in hot paths.
- Iterators over manual indexing.
- `&[T]` parameters over `Vec<T>` (caller can pass either).
- `Cow<'_, T>` when borrowing usually works but occasionally needs to
  own.
- `#[inline]` only when you've measured.
